The main difference between using a Case Statement and an If-Else statement in Actian 4GL OpenROAD lies in their structure and functionality. While an If-Else statement allows for two or more mutually exclusive conditional blocks, a Case Statement provides a way to select one of several possible actions based on the value of an expression. Additionally, the syntax for both statements is different:
```
if condition then
   // Statements for true condition
elseif condition then
   // Statements for second condition
else
   // Statements for all other cases
end if;
```
versus
```
case key of
  valuelist: statement | beginendblock
  {valuelist: statement | beginendblock}
endcase;
```

Here is an example of how to use a Case Statement in Actian 4GL OpenROAD:
```
case inputselection of
          'Beginner',
          begin_synonym :
          {
               field(menu.edit_menu.paste).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
               field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
               curframe.WindowTitle = curframe.WindowTitle + 'Beginner';
          }
          'Intermediate',
          inter_synonym :
          {
               field(menu.edit_menu.paste).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
               /*
               ** Do advanced stuff also.
               */
               nextcase;
          }
          'Advanced',
          advance_synonym :
          {
               field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_ENABLED;
          }
          default:
               message 'Unknown selection' + inputselection + '!';
          endcase;
```

Here is an example code snippet that demonstrates using multiple case blocks with the fall-through feature and a default block:
```
case inputselection of
    'Beginner':
        field(menu.edit_menu.paste).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
        field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
        curframe.WindowTitle = curframe.WindowTitle + 'Beginner';
    'Intermediate':
        /* Do advanced stuff also. */
        nextcase;
    'Advanced':
        field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_ENABLED;
    default:
        message 'Unknown selection' + inputselection + '!';
endcase;
```

In an Actian 4GL OpenROAD Case Statement, you can use a single statement within a case block if only one action needs to be executed for that case. However, if multiple actions need to be executed for the same case, you should use a begin-end block to enclose those statements. Here is an example code snippet:
```
case inputselection of
    'Beginner':
        field(menu.edit_menu.paste).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
        field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
        curframe.WindowTitle = curframe.WindowTitle + 'Beginner';
    'Intermediate':
        begin
            /* Do advanced stuff also. */
        end;
    'Advanced':
        field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_ENABLED;
endcase;
```

To assign different values to another variable `value` based on the value of a string data type variable `inputselection` using an Actian 4GL OpenROAD Case Statement, you can use the following code:
```
case lowercase(inputselection) of
     'Beginner' : value = 1;
     'Intermediate' : value = 2;
     'Advanced' : value = 3;
endcase;
```

An example of a Case Statement with multiple conditions in Actian 4GL OpenROAD is as follows:

```
case age of
       0: if gender = 'male' then message('Baby boy') else message('Baby girl');
      1-2: message('Toddler');
      3-5: case grade of
            'A': message('Excellent work!');
            'B': message('Good job, keep up the good work.');
            default: message('You could do better. Try again.')
          endcase;
       6-12: case occupation of
             'student' : message('Keep learning and growing');
             'teacher'  : message('Great teachers are important.');
             default    : message('Work hard and pursue your dreams.');
         endcase;
     else message('Invalid age or gender');
endcase;
```
In this example, the first condition checks if the age is equal to 0. If it is, the code inside the block checks the value of the 'gender' variable and outputs a different message depending on its value. The second condition checks if the age is between 1 and 2 or between 3 and 5, each with a nested case statement that performs a different action based on the value of another variable ('grade').

In a Case Statement, when you don't explicitly specify 'nextcase' to jump from one case block to the next, it is called a fall-through case. If there are multiple blocks with matching valuelist elements and no 'nextcase', then the statements in those blocks will execute sequentially until a different case is matched or the end of the Case Statement is reached.

For example:
```
case inputselection of
          'Beginner',
          {
               field(menu.edit_menu.paste).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
               field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
               curframe.WindowTitle = curframe.WindowTitle + 'Beginner';
          }
          'Intermediate',
          {
               field(menu.edit_menu.paste).curbias = MB_INVISIBLE;
               /*
               ** Do advanced stuff also.
               */
               nextcase;
          }
          'Advanced',
          {
               field(menu.file_menu.save_spec).curbias = MB_ENABLED;
          }
```
In the example above, since there's no 'nextcase' specified in the Intermediate case block, it will execute the statements in both Beginner and Intermediate blocks because of fall-through when inputselection equals 'Intermediate'.

